\begin_layout Section
Equivalent Optimization Problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\reals^{d}\to\reals$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\reals^{d}\to\reals$
\end_inset

.
 Now consider the following optimization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min_{x\in\reals^{d}}f(x)+g(x).
\]

\end_inset

This is an unconstrained optimization problem.
 Let's also consider the following constrained optimization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\textrm{minimize} &  & f(x)+\xi\\
\textrm{subject to} &  & \xi\ge g(x).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

When an optimization problem is presented in this form, it should be understood
 as a minimization over all variables that are unknown.
 In this case, we are minimizing over 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\reals^{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in\reals$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We claim that these two problems are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equivalent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the following sense:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose the second problem attains a minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{*},\xi^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

, and that minimum is 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then the first problem also has a minimum value of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and it is attained at 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 [It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi^{*}=g(x^{*})$
\end_inset

.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Conversely, if the first problem attains a minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

, then there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi^{*}$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{*},\xi^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a minimizer of the second problem, and the minimum values are the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Convince yourself that these two problems are equivalent.
 [Hint/Answer: In the second problem, for any fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the objective is always minimized (subject to the constraint) by 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=g(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
The equivalence shown above is a very strict equivalence.
 We may also speak more loosely and say that two problems are equivalent
 if we can easily derive a solution to one of them given a solution to the
 other one, even if the minimizers and minima are different.
 For example, if we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\argmin_{x}\exp\left[f(2x)\right]=x^{*}$
\end_inset

, then we can immediately conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\argmin_{x}f(x)=2x^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

